    <note>Shen(2) Bo [7326] Jichang's [1445] and Shutong's [1458] father, Yuan(2) Haowen's [7410] son-in-law. Zeng(1) Gong [7364] was a tongnianyou of Bo's father-in-law, Yuan(2) Haowen [7410], as well as a friend (you) of Bo's sons. His great grandson, Du [3737], was Liangzhe yunfu between 1167 and 1172. According to Wang Anshi, Bo used the jinshi to establish his family branch of the lineage (qijia)--even though his direct patrilineal ancestors held office continuously from ancestor Jiji [20877], who was recommended for office by Yang(2) Yan(3) [20876] in Tang--including two Tang jinshi (son and grandson of Jiji]. His great grandfather, Tingpin [20882], was probably the ancestor, who moved from Huzhou, Wukang county to Hangzhou, Qiantang county (modern Hangxian), and his father, Yu(2) [20883], who once served as prefect of Zhenzhou, probably moved there where Bo was buried. Bo's lineage and that of Shen(2) Zhou [7323] et. al., probably have a common ancestor. Xianchun Linan zhi, 50.7b, 8a; SHY:SH, 50.25a; Zeng Gong, WJ, 45.11b-12b (wife, born Yuan, who died in 1065 at age 70, was a widow at age 30+ [thereby dating death of Bo in ca. 1025, but he served at least two full terms before death, which would place death in ca. 1028 when wife was age 35--other dates estimated on this basis]); Wang Anshi, WJ, 90.936-937. CBD, 1, 685-6.</note>
